The {{Nihongo|'''Ōita Prefectural Art Museum'''|大分県立美術館|Ōitakenritsu Bijutsukan}}, also known informally as '''OpAm''', is an art museum and community exhibition venue in [[Ōita Prefecture]], [[Japan]].
The museum is located in the center of the prefectural capital [[Ōita, Ōita|Ōita-shi]], a 15 minute walk north-west of [[Ōita Station]].
==Current facilities== The museum was opened in April 2015. The new museum building features modern exhibition spaces, artists studios, a café and museum shop. The building was designed by [[Pritzker Architecture Prize]] winning architect [[Shigeru Ban]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Peregoy|first1=Beau|title=The Shigeru Ban–designed Oita Prefectural Art Museum Opens in Japan|url=http://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/oita-prefectural-art-museum-shigeru-ban|website=Architectural Digest|accessdate=10 July 2017}}</ref> At the ground level the building features fully retractable glass shutters opening the main internal exhibition space onto an adjacent public plaza.
The building was the recipient of a [[RIBA International Award]] for excellence in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=RIBA International Prize|url=https://www.architecture.com/awards-and-competitions-landing-page/awards/riba-international-prize|website=Royal Institute of British Architects|accessdate=10 July 2017}}</ref>
